Title : Juliet Kono
Text : '''Juliet Kono''', married once to David Lee so once writing as '''Juliet Kono Lee''', is a Hawaiian poet and novelist. A former police dispatcher who took up writing while on the job,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbshawaii.org/ourproductions/longstory_transcripts/LSS%20424%20Transcript%20-%20Juliet%20Lee.pdf|title=Interview with author Juliet S. Kono|last=Wilcox|first=Leslie|date=July 12, 2011|publisher=PBS Hawaii|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref> she graduated from the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] before becoming an instructor in English at [[Leeward Community College]]. She has also taught at [[Wellesley College]] and the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name="sourcebook">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AwEtBiiphOoC&pg=PA173 |title=''Asian-American Poets: A Bio-bibliographical Critical Sourcebook''|last=Huang|first=Guiyou|year=2002|page=173|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref>

Kono received a Creative Artist Exchange Fellowship from the Japan-United States Friendship Commission in 1998<ref name="sourcebook"/> and the Hawaii Award for Literature in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawaii.gov/sfca/literature.html|title=Recipients of Past Hawai'i Awards for Literature|date=May 15, 2014|publisher=Hawaii State Foundation on Culture and the Arts|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref> She is considered a member of the ''[[Bamboo Ridge]]'' group of writers<ref name="sourcebook"/> and also serves as a Buddhist priest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bambooridge.com/feature.aspx?fid=171|title=Interview with author Juliet S. Kono|last=Staff report|year=2010|publisher=Bamboo Ridge Press|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref> Her novel ''Anshu: Dark Sorrow'' received the 2011 Ka Palapala Po'okela Book Award for Literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/20110515_Juliet_Konos_Anshu_captures_Pookela_award_for_literature_.html|title=Juliet Kono's 'Anshu' captures Po'okela award for literature|last=Staff report|date=May 15, 2011|publisher=''Honolulu Star-Advertiser''|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref>

==Bibliography==
*''Hilo Rains'' (1988)
*''Sister Stew: Poetry and Fiction by Women'' (1991) (with [[Cathy Song]])
*''Tsunami Years'' (1995)
*''How the Ocean Fooled Us'' (1997) (with Emi Fukawa)
*''A Day on the Cyclo'' (2000)
*''The Pancake Place'' (2000)
*''Ho'olulu Park and the Pepsodent Smile, and Other Stories'' (2004)
*''The Bravest Opihi'' (2005)
*''Anshu: Dark Sorrow'' (2010)

